High Priority Network (HPN) Tool

This tool presents a draft High Priority Network (HPN) that prioritizes segments and junctions with high fatal and serious injury crash rates through a combination of need and risk.


The analysis sets the groundwork for a targeted Safety Action Plan expected to be complete by Fall 2025. The analysis, utilizing 2018 2022 crash data through hotspot and systemic risk based analysis, underscores the critical areas where interventions can significantly enhance road safety and reduce fatal and serious injury crashes.

config.text: High Risk Attributes

The Safe Streets for All (SS4A) team conducted a Systemic Based (Risk/Causality) Analysis uses a machine learning model (Random Forest) that identifies features of the regional roadway and intersections that correlate with fatalities and serious injuries regardless of whether such events occurred recently. The goal is to flag infrastructure with roadway features (e.g., lane count) that may increase the likelihood of future severe incidents on the network. The resulting attribute of this work is a Risk Score that calls attention to particularly risky roadway and junction facilities and a High Risk Network.


The following are the top five highest correlated attributes that were used to determine high risk:


Intersections:

  • Average Lane Widths on approaches of 12 feet or more feet
  • Four or more number of legs
  • Posted Speed on an approach of 35 miles per hour or greater
  • 60/120 degree intersections
  • Four or more lanes on the major approach


Roads:

  • Designated as a Principal Arterial functional class
  • Posted Speed of 25 miles per hour or greater
  • No median or 16+ foot medians
  • Lane Width of 12 or more feet
  • Identified as an "Experienced Riders" bike facility route

Safety Need

The Safe Streets for All (SS4A) team utilize information on historical need to develop a High Priority Network (HPN). Find more information about each of those layers below:


  • Community Survey - Member of the community identified segments and junctions that were of safety concern. These points were utilized to develop the Community Survey Network. Click here to access the survey.
  • Crashes (2018-2022) - Five years of crash data from the Nebraska and Iowa Departments of Transportation were used to develop the High Injury Network and Risk Attributes used in the High Risk Network.
High Priority Network
Mean Priority Score

This score is the average (using mean) priority score of all the features shown on the map. The priority score is a combination of three scores (location, community, and risk) that has a maximum total value of 300. The mean priority score assists in finding the relation between different areas and safety priority.
